Now even in its most moderate form, this assumptionis considerably opposed to the usual course of ethnological changes, or rather the usual course of ethnological changes is opposed to it. ln the first place, there are two cases of the incorporated and amalgamated aborigines of a country taking the name of their conquerors to one of the converse process. Thus Franco takes its name from the German Franks, and England from the German English, instead of the Franks taking their name from the Gaula, or the Angles from the Britons.
